== About Me
I am  an Assistant Professor in the School of Mathematical Sciences and Center for Machine Learning Research at Peking University.

Previously, I was a postdoctoral researcher at PACM, Princeton University and at the Wharton School, University of Pennsylvania.
I received my Ph.D. in Computational Mathematics from Peking University in 2018, advised by Prof. Weinan E, and my B.S. in Mathematics from Nankai University in 2012.

I aim to develop a *predictive science of deep learning* by connecting insights from tractable surrogate models with real-world training, spanning kernel methods, neural networks, and modern *LLM pretraining*. See [research.html Research] for my research vision and selected highlights.


== Recruiting

We are actively seeking self-motivated postdocs, PhD students, and undergraduate students interested in the *scientific foundations of deep learning*, particularly approximation, optimization, *scaling laws*, and *LLM pretraining*.

If you are interested in joining our group, please email me your CV, transcript (for student applicants), and a brief description of your background and research interests.



== Recent Updates

- 2026-07: I will teach a short course on *Foundations of Deep Learning: Approximation, Generalization, and Scaling* at [https://yingzhouli.com/others/FDUSS2026/index-mass-en.html 2026 Fudan University International Summer School on AI in Math].

- 2026-07: Co-organized the [https://ml-math-2026.github.io/ 2026 PKU Workshop on Mathematical Foundations of Modern Machine Learning] with [https://www.lfhsgre.org/ Fanghui Liu] and [https://kunyuan827.github.io/ Kun Yuan].

- 2026-06: [https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.06797 Optimal Learning-Rate Schedules under Functional Scaling Laws: Power Decay and Warmup-Stable-Decay] accepted to *COLT 2026*.

- 2026-06: [https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.24275 GradPower: Powering Gradients for Faster Language Model Pre-Training] accepted to *ICML 2026*.

- 2026-02: [https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.19691 Smoothness Adaptivity in Constant-Depth Neural Networks: Optimal Rates via Smooth Activations] released on arXiv.

- 2026-02: [https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.14208 Fast Catch-Up, Late Switching: Optimal Batch Size Scheduling via Functional Scaling Laws] accepted to *ICLR 2026*.

- 2025-09: [https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.19189 Functional Scaling Laws in Kernel Regression: Loss Dynamics and Learning Rate Schedules] accepted to *NeurIPS 2025 (Spotlight)*.